---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import CassettePlayer from '../components/CassettePlayer.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead
			title={`Consulting — ${SITE_TITLE}`}
			description="Mobile payments architecture audits for consumer Android apps with >100K MAU — two-week engagement, written report, 90-minute readout."
		/>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<section class="reveal">
				<p class="eyebrow">Consulting</p>
				<h1>Mobile payments architecture audit.</h1>
				<p class="tagline">
					A focused, two-week engagement for consumer Android apps
					with &gt;100K MAU. I find the cracks in your subscription
					stack before your users do.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section class="reveal">
				<h2>Who this is for</h2>
				<ul class="check-list">
					<li>You run a consumer mobile app with subscription revenue on Google Play.</li>
					<li>You have &gt;100K MAU and recurring billing complexity (renewals, upgrades, refunds, edge cases).</li>
					<li>You suspect there&rsquo;s revenue leakage, hidden instability, or accumulating tech debt in your billing stack &mdash; but no one internally has time to dig in.</li>
					<li>You want a senior outside read in writing, not a sales pitch.</li>
				</ul>
			</section>

			<section class="reveal">
				<h2>What you get</h2>
				<ol class="numbered-list">
					<li>
						<strong>Architecture review.</strong>
						I read your billing-related code, your subscription state machine,
						your receipt-verification flow, and the surrounding observability.
						I look at it the way I look at Adobe Acrobat&rsquo;s &mdash;
						the same lens that ships Play Billing changes to 95M+ MAU without
						incidents.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Findings report.</strong>
						A written document organized by severity (P0/P1/P2), each finding
						with: the issue, the user-visible impact, the revenue/stability
						risk, and a concrete remediation. Nothing vague.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Readout call.</strong>
						A 90-minute video call with your engineering &amp; product
						leadership to walk through findings, prioritize, and answer
						questions live.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>30 days of async follow-up.</strong>
						As your team starts the remediation work, you can email me
						questions or share a PR for spot review. No new meetings,
						just unblocking.
					</li>
				</ol>
			</section>

			<section class="reveal">
				<h2>Scope &amp; pricing</h2>
				<ul class="meta-list">
					<li><span>Duration</span> <strong>2 weeks, fixed.</strong></li>
					<li><span>Format</span> <strong>Async + 90-minute readout call.</strong></li>
					<li><span>Pricing</span> <strong>From $3,500 USD</strong>, scoped per engagement.</li>
					<li><span>Availability</span> <strong>2&ndash;3 engagements / quarter.</strong> Booked first-come.</li>
				</ul>
				<p class="fine-print">
					Pricing is intentionally bespoke &mdash; complexity varies. I&rsquo;ll
					give you a fixed number after a 20-minute scoping call.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section class="reveal">
				<h2>Why me</h2>
				<p>
					I own end-to-end stability of Adobe Acrobat Android&rsquo;s
					in-app payments stack &mdash; one of the most-installed Android
					apps in the world. I&rsquo;ve shipped Acrobat Mobile&rsquo;s
					first cross-product subscription upgrade / downgrade /
					cross-grade architecture (Jan 2026, zero production incidents
					since launch, adopted by other Acrobat apps), instituted the
					controlled-rollback playbook for payments, and reduced
					payment-related incidents 23% quarter-over-quarter.
				</p>
				<p>
					What I bring isn&rsquo;t generic mobile architecture advice.
					It&rsquo;s a specific lens on subscription state machines,
					revenue observability, and the failure modes that show up at
					billion-install scale.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section class="reveal">
				<h2>Get in touch</h2>
				<div class="soft-cta">
					<p>
						Tell me a bit about your app (MAU, what flavor of subscription complexity,
						any recent incidents), and I&rsquo;ll come back with a 20-minute
						scoping-call slot.
					</p>
					<p>
						<a class="primary-btn" href="mailto:rishabh@rishabhships.com?subject=Mobile%20payments%20audit%20inquiry">Email rishabh@rishabhships.com &rarr;</a>
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>
		</main>
		<Footer />
		<CassettePlayer />

		<style>
			.eyebrow {
				font-size: 0.85em;
				color: var(--accent-dark);
				font-weight: 600;
				text-transform: uppercase;
				letter-spacing: 0.1em;
				margin-bottom: 0.5em;
			}
			.tagline {
				font-size: 1.15em;
				color: var(--ink-muted);
				margin-bottom: 2em;
			}
			.check-list, .numbered-list {
				padding-left: 1.3em;
			}
			.check-list li, .numbered-list li {
				margin-bottom: 0.9em;
			}
			.meta-list {
				list-style: none;
				padding: 0;
				margin: 1em 0;
				border: 1px solid var(--border);
				border-radius: 12px;
				background: var(--bg-elevated);
				overflow: hidden;
			}
			.meta-list li {
				display: flex;
				justify-content: space-between;
				gap: 1em;
				padding: 0.85em 1.2em;
				border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
				font-size: 0.97em;
			}
			.meta-list li:last-child { border-bottom: 0; }
			.meta-list li > span {
				color: var(--ink-soft);
				font-weight: 500;
			}
			.fine-print {
				font-size: 0.88em;
				color: var(--ink-muted);
				margin-top: 0.6em;
			}
			.primary-btn {
				display: inline-block;
				padding: 0.7em 1.4em;
				background: var(--accent);
				color: white;
				border-radius: 8px;
				text-decoration: none;
				font-weight: 600;
				transition: background 0.18s ease, transform 0.18s ease, box-shadow 0.18s ease;
			}
			.primary-btn:hover {
				background: var(--accent-dark);
				color: white;
				transform: translateY(-1px);
				box-shadow: 0 8px 18px rgba(13, 148, 136, 0.22);
				text-decoration: none;
			}
		</style>
	</body>
</html>
